Introduction¶

Sentiment analysis, also referred to as opinion mining, is an approach to natural language processing (NLP) that identifies the emotional tone behind a body of text. This is a popular way for organizations to determine and categorize opinions about a product, service or idea.

The objective of this study is to understand and implement a method of subfield study of NLP which is to transform the words into vectors, and to apply different machine learning models including Logistic Regression, Decision Tree Classifier, Random Forest, K-nearest neighbors, Support Vector Machine, Naive Bayes to a dataset of moview reviews to classify the movie reviews into positive or negative category.

Description of dataset¶

The Internet Movie Database(IMDb) that has been collected by Andrew Mass and other (Andrew L. Maas, Raymond E. Daly, Peter T. Pham, Dan Huang, Andrew Y. Ng, and Christopher Potts. (2011). Learning Word Vectors for Sentiment Analysis. The 49th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL 2011)).

The movie review dataset consists of 50,000 popular movie reviews that are labeled as either positive or negative. A positive means that a movie received more than six stars on IMDb, and a negative means that a movie was rated with less than five stars on IMDb.

We will have to extract meaningful information from a subset of of these movie reviews to develop a machine learning model that predicts whether a certain reviewer liked of disliked a movie.

Obtaining the dataset¶

You can either download the dataset in a csv file from Kaggle at following link https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/hamditarek/imdb-dataset-50k-maas-et-al-2011
The csv file is about 80 mb, quite large.
Or a compressed archive of the dataset can be downloaded from https://ai.stanford.edu/~amaas/data/sentiment/
I downloaded the archive file directly from Andrew Mass personal website at Standford University and use Python to extract the tar file.

Preprocessing the dataset¶

Having fully extracted the dataset, I will have to assemble the individual text documents from the decompressed folder into a single CSV file. The dataset was split into 25,000 samples for train in the train folder and 25,000 samples for test in the test folder. And in each folder, the data was split into subsequent folders named pos for positive reviews, and neg for negative reviews. So basically we have two features here: Review and Sentiment. I will create a dataframe and store the individual text as review and its sentiment appropriately for all the data. This could take up to 5-10 minutes depending on the processor of the computer you are working on.

In [2]:
import pandas as pd
import os

basepath = 'aclImdb'
lables = {'pos':1, 'neg':0}
df = pd.DataFrame()

for i in ('test', 'train'):
    for j in ('pos','neg'):
        path = os.path.join(basepath,i,j)
        for file in sorted(os.listdir(path)):
            with open(os.path.join(path,file),'r', encoding = 'utf-8') as infile:
                txt = infile.read()
                df = df.append([[txt,lables[j]]], ignore_index= True)
df.columns =['review','sentiment']

I can see that the text contains HTML markup as well as punctuation, other non-letters. I will remove them except for emoticons character such as :). I use the Python's regular expression lbirary for the task.

In [15]:
import re
def preprocessor(text):
    text = re.sub('<[^>]*>','',text)
    emoticons = re.findall('(?::|;|-)(?:-)?(?:\)|\(D|P)',text)
    text = (re.sub('[\W]+',' ',text.lower()) + ' '.join(emoticons).replace('-',''))
    return text

The first regex <[^>]*> is to remove all the HTML markups. The second regex (?::|;|-)(?:-)?(?:)|(D|P) is to find all the emoticons in the text. And the last regex [\W]+ is to remove all the non-words character. Finally I convert text into lowercase and combine with the emoticon attached at the end of the text. Let's see if the function preprocessor is working well.

Stop-word removal: Stop-words are simply the words that are very common in all sort of texts and probably contain no useful information that can be used. Examples of stop-words are is, are, and, have, has, like, etc. We can use the 'stopwords' libary from NLTK library.

In [19]:
import nltk
nltk.download('stopwords')
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
def stop_words(text):
    stop = stopwords.words('english')
    return [w for w in tokenizer(text) if w not in stop]

Finding the most frequent words in the dataset including most frequent words for positive and negative comments

In [21]:
from collections import defaultdict

def vocab_count(docs):
    vocab = defaultdict(int)
    for doc in docs:
        for token in doc:            
            if token not in vocab:
                    vocab[token] = 1 
            else:
                    vocab[token] += 1
    return vocab

Transforming words into feature vector:The bag-of-words model, which allows us to represent text as numerical features.

  1. Create a vocabulary of unique tokens such as words from the entire set of documents.
  2. Construct a vector from each document that contains the counts of how often each word occurs in the particular document.

Because we have such quite large dataset. It will take a lot of computer memory to vectorize all the words. However the scipy kit provides a sparse matrix class called csr_matrix which is a compressed matrix, very efficient for computing and caluclating matrix.Let's use that and see how MyCountVectorizer works.

In [25]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix

class MyCountVectorizer:
    
    def __init__(self):    
        self.vocab = {}
    def fit_transform(self, docs):
        
        #build vocabulary
        
        for doc in docs:
            for token in doc:
                if token not in self.vocab:
                    self.vocab[token] = len(self.vocab) #set the token value = length of vocab at setting
                         
        #build document-term matrix
        #each row represents a document and each column represents a token in the vocabulary
        #the value at the intersection of row i and column j represents the count of the jth token in the ith document
        
        row = []
        col = []
        data = []
        for i, doc in enumerate(docs):
            for token in doc:
                row.append(i)
                col.append(self.vocab[token])
                data.append(doc.count(token))
        return csr_matrix((data, (row, col)), shape=(len(docs), len(self.vocab)))

A method to downweight the frequently occuring words in the feature vectors called term frequency-inverse document frequency (tf-idf). The tf-idf can be defined as the product of the term frequency and the inverse document frequency: tf-idf(t,d)=tf(t,d)xidf(t,d).
Here tf(t,d) is the term frequency and idf(t,d) is the inverse document frequency which is computed as follows: idf(t,d) = log((n)/(1+df(t,d)) where df(t,d) is the number of documents that contains the term and n is the total number of documents.
Please note that sklearn has all the libraries such as CountVectorizer or TfidfVectorizer that do all the works for us, however because of the objective of this study I will try to implement from the scratch to understand the way it works around.

In [27]:
import numpy as np

class MyTfidfTransformer:
    
    def __init__(self):    
        self.doc_term_matrix = None
        self.idf = None
    
    def fit_transform(self, doc_term_matrix):
        #build document-term matrix
        self.doc_term_matrix = doc_term_matrix
        
        #calculate IDF for each term
        df = np.sum(doc_term_matrix != 0, axis=0)
        idf = np.log((doc_term_matrix.shape[0]) / (df + 1))  
        self.idf = csr_matrix(idf)
        
        #calculate TF-IDF for each document-term pair
        self.doc_term_matrix = self.doc_term_matrix.multiply(self.idf)
        
        #Normalize the weight by L2-normalization
        self.doc_term_matrix = self.doc_term_matrix.multiply(1.0 / np.sqrt(self.doc_term_matrix.power(2).sum(axis=1)))
                
        return self.doc_term_matrix

After implementing MyTfidfTransformer, I use its function to convert review column into vector. I will save the data as X for all review vector array, and y as prediction array

I want to develop a few help functions to caculate precision as well as recall, to plot ROC curve and confusion matrix

In [31]:
def calculate_precision(y_true, y_pred, pos_label_value=1.0):
    
    from sklearn.metrics import precision_score
    
    return precision_score(y_true,y_pred, pos_label=pos_label_value)

def calculate_recall(y_true, y_pred, pos_label_value=1.0):
   
    
    from sklearn.metrics import recall_score
    
    return recall_score(y_true,y_pred, pos_label=pos_label_value)

def plot_roc(y_test,y_pred):
    
    from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
    from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    
    fpr,tpr, th = roc_curve(y_test,y_pred[:,1])
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred[:,1])
    plt.plot(fpr,tpr)
    plt.plot(np.arange(0,1.1,0.1), np.arange(0,1.1,0.1), 'r--')
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    plt.title("ROC Curve")
    plt.text(0.7,0.2,'AUC=' + "{:.3f}".format(auc))
    plt.show()

def plot_confusion_matrix(conf_matrix):    
    
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(4,3), dpi=100)
    
    sns.set(font_scale = 1.1)

    ax = sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', )
   
    ax.set_xlabel("Prediction", fontsize=14, labelpad=20)
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['Negative', 'Positive'])

    ax.set_ylabel("Actual", fontsize=14, labelpad=20)
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['Negative', 'Positive'])

    ax.set_title("Confusion Matrix", fontsize=14, pad=20)

    plt.show()

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
def build_dt(data_X, data_y, max_depth = None, max_leaf_nodes =None):
    
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = max_depth,max_leaf_nodes = max_leaf_nodes)
    return clf.fit(data_X, data_y)

Support Vector Machine¶

I will have to implement a predict probability function for LinearSVC since it does not have the predict_proba function. Also, I can use SVC with kerner ='linear' but it takes much longer time to compute than LinearSVC and gives the same result

In [56]:
import numpy as np

def LinearSVC_predict_proba(model, X):
    # Compute the distances between each sample and the decision hyperplane
    distances = model.decision_function(X)
    
    # Convert distances to probabilities using a calibrated sigmoid function
    proba = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-distances))
    proba = np.vstack([1 - proba, proba]).T
    
    return proba

The table shows that Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Linear SVM, and Naive Bayes seem to be the approriate models for this sentiment analysis. Meanwhile Decision Tree or K-nearest Neighbors seem to underperform. Out of the 4 models that perform well, Linear SVM seems to be the best model with the highest accuracy, and highest AUC. However, Logistic Regression actually does really well too, almost comparable to Linear SVM. In term of computing efficiency, Naive Bayes would be the fastest. But Logistic Regression and Linear SVM are quite fast, while Random Forest is the slowest one because of brute force search.

Conclusion¶

The study helped me learn how to use machine learning algorithms to classify text document based on their polairty, a basic task in sentiment analysis in the field of NFP. I learnt how to encode a document as a feature vector using the bag-of-words model, and also learnt how to weight frequency by using tf-idf.

Through working on the project, I found that apply machine learning algorithm on text data can be computationally expensivve because of large data, or large feature vectors. I had to find ways to work around, find efficient algorithm to convert and calculate the vectors. One solution can be used if I can use mini-batch algorithm to do the job but it is certainly out of scope for the supervised learning.

Further improvements can certainly apply for example using stemming words or lemmatizing words. One can also question whether or not removing the most frequent words on both classifications, those would not affect sentiment analysis, will give a better result. I found evidence that removing words like 'movie' or 'film' increase Random Forest algorithm performance while do not decrease other models performance much. So all of these could be further studies for me.
